{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_genesis_ver01/data/sn82014519/00414219767/1927062401/1013.xml":{"full_text":"NEW BRITAIN DAILY HERALD, FRIDAY, JUNE 24, 1927.\nFLASHES OF LIFE: NERVY AUTOISTS\nASK POLICE FOR SPECIAL ESCORTS\ntoy the Associated Press.\nRoosevelt, Field, N. Y. Mr. Byrd\nis \"Uncle Commander Dick\" to some\nchildren with the same name as this\nhome of aircraft. Four smiles and\nTour seta ot white teeth such a\nmade their grandfather's smile fam\nous were noted when Theodore\nKoosevelt, 3d, his brother, Quentin,\nJits sister, Grace and his cousin,\nKdith Derby were photographed\nlooking; out of the cabin of the plane\nAmerica.\nNewark, Ji. J. Rather than have\nUie first submarine of John P. Hol\nland, inventor of the submersible,\ngo to the junk pile, his son, Joseph\nintends to buy it if possible, take it\nout to sea and have it sunk. Given\nto a military school 11 years ago, the\nsubmarine was sold recently a junk\nman for 1100 because of difficulty\nin removing it to the school's new\nvile.\nCleveland Some crusty impostors\nhave been stepping on the gas in\ntouring Ohio by automobile. Police\nof various towns between here and\nToledo got telegrams from Detroit\nasking police motorcycle escorts for\nLindbergh and his mother. And so\na car containing a young man, an\nelderly woman and a boy got the\nright of way.\nNew York \"A slender, blonde\ndaisy\" is the hero of a novel that is\nselling rapidly in Hungary, whose\nchampion stenographer wrote it.\nBudapest newspapers tell of Michael\nLorant reading thousands of news\npaper clippings about Lindbergh's\nflight and getting therefrom ma\nterial for \"The Hero of the Ocean.\"\nPittsburgh, Pa. Airplane propel\nler blades have been sent by Admiral\nto Oakland, Calif., for Richard D.\nGrace, who hopes to use them in a\nflight to Honolulu. The postage on\na 90-pound shipment was $273.\nNew York With his airedale.\nwhose transportation by airplane for\n600 miles cost him $105, Michael J.\nSpellacy, mining engineer, is back\nfrom Bogota. The company op\nerating the plane from Bogota to\nPort l.imon ruled the dog was ex\ncess baggage.\nNew Haven Diving into shallow\nwater at Savin Rock, William Ber\nman; 18, fractures fifth vertebra of\nneck; expected to recover.\nBridgeport Word received of\ndeath in Paris of Baroness D'Alex\nandry, widow of P. T. Barnum, fam\nous showman.\nMeriden Plans for establish\nment of air field announced.\nBridgeport Raid on cherry tree\nfollowed by shooting of James Yan\ncoli, 13, through left hip with small\nrifle by irate owner.\nNew Haven Prospects are that\ntrolleymen's demands for new wage\nand time schedules will go to arbi\ntration; conversations are continuing.\nNew Haven Loom Zimkowsi,\nbusiness man, with party of pilgrims\nto Rome and Germany, dies in\nMunich.\nNew Haven Col. E. li. Averill,\nBranford, made deputy attorney\ngeneraf.\nand sets out that it is an equitable\naction, but the sheriff to the' court,\nhas attached the premises of the\ndefendant.\n\"Under article 3, section 1, of the\nConstitution of the United States,\nthe judicial power of the United\nStates shall be vested in one Su\npreme court, and in such inferior\ncourts as the congress may from\ntime to time ordain or establish;\nand the courts of the state of Con\nnecticut are not ordained or estab\nlished by congress and are not\namenable to that body, and Con\ngress can not vest any portion of the\njudicial power of the United States\nin the courts of the state of Con\nnecticut. \"The city court for the city of\nNew Britain has no Inherent power\nand cannot acquire through the\nact of congress the requisite authori-\nHartford State's payroll in\ncreased by many thousands of dol\nlars through salary increases to\nvarious state commissioners and\nsubordinate officials.\nHartford Dr. Edward Beecher\nHooker, descendant of the earliest\nof Connecticut colonists, nephew of\nRev. Henry Ward Beecher, dies.\nMOTION TO QUASH\nBoston There's such a thing as\nplenty of room at the top with lit\ntle at bottom. The police forced a\nsteeplejack who had spent three\ndays on top of a flagpole and wanted\nto stay there to descend because\nmotorists in the narrow Boston\nstreet were craning their necks and\ninviting accidents.\nLondon The Prince of Wales\nwound up his 33rd birthday by going\nto a fancy ball dressed as a school\nboy. He and Prince George wore\nshort Eton jackets, big turned down\ncollars, pink bow ties and white\nsocks. The Duchess of Westminster,\ndressed as a baby,, was wheeled into\nthe ballroom in a baby carriage.\nParis King Alfonso drove him\nself in an electric locomotive part of\nthe way to Paris. He went to the\nhead of the train at the frontier\ntown of Hendaye.\nLawyer Makes Move in Mary\nWisk Liquor Case\nA motion to quash the temporary\ni injunction granted in city court by\nJudge W. C. Hungerford in the ac\nI tion of the United States of America\nagainst Mrs. Mary Wisk, has been\nj tiled by Aattorney Donald Gaffney,\n307 Lafayette street, in the build\ning owned b\"y Mrs. Wisk, because\nof numerous violations of the liquor\nlaw.\nIn his motion to quash the in\njunction. Attorney Gaffney sets\nforth the following reasons:\n\"It does not appear that the ap\nj plication for an injunction is based\non any law of the state of Connecti-\ncut.\n\"The City Court of New Britain\nand the judge ot the said court is\nwithout jurisdiction to hear and de-\nI termine said application.\nI \"The written application for an\nI injunction pretends to be based on\nsection 22, title 2, of the National\nProhibition Act, a United States\nI statute, and offenses against said\ni act are not cognizable by the courts\nI of the state of Connecticut or by\nj the judges of said courts.\n\"The writ demands no damages\nOssining, N. Y. More people have\nbeen trying to get into Sing Sing\nprison than those who are trying to\nget out. Visitors have been run\nning as high as 3,000 a day and\nthey have been holding picnics on\nthe prison grounds. Picnics! arc to\nbe forbidden and the number ot\ncurious gaping at convicts is to be\ncurtailed.\nRapid City, S. D. Rebecca has\ngone and freed herself. The pet\nraccoon fled the summer White\nHouse and went up a tall pine.\nPeking Clever, these Chinese!\nSundry gambling and opium joints\nare operated by women. As a re\nsult a school has been opened for\nthe training of women detectives.\nNew Haven Fifteen Yale track\nmen leave to join eight from Har\nvard on trip to England to meet\njoint Cambridge-Oxford team.\nHartford Office of state athletic\ncommissions made full time by\nstate board of finance and control,\nand Commissioner T. E. Donahue\ngiven salary of $5,000.\nNew London Yale's combination\ncrew draws first blood against\nHarvard in annual races, winning by\nsix seconds over two-mile course.\nMiddlehaddam Carl Lund, 1B-year-old\norphanage inmate, drowns\nwhile in swimming.\nMiddletown An aunt, 17, and her\nniece. 18, graduate from high school\nin same class. They are Miss Mae\nDean and Miss Olva M Dean.\nNew Haven Unconscious and\nsinking for third time. Miss Angelia\nSchvone, 22, is rescued by Albert\nPlscitelli, 14.\nLAYER CAKE\nM cup butter H cup milk\n1 cup sugar 1 cups flout\n2 eggs 2H taps, baking powder\n16 op. Baiter's Vanilla Extract\nH tsp. Baker's Lemon Extract\nV rsp. Baker's Orange Extract\nCream butter and sugar, add\neggs, beaten, and milk. Sift\nflour with baking powder,\nadd to other ingredients. Fla\nvor and bake in layer cake\npans. This makes three layers.\nMay my send you a ttnm\n1.\nI ertnutamMeoi Bailer's\nVanilla Extract and A,\nY also ow bookUt of over ysj\n1 1 00 tested recipes BotK ff\nare free Wriufor them.\nWauh our ads for Faumte JUcipo\n\"Plavsr totter\nwith SUHM'S\"\nCJhtijood\nBAKER'S\nCERTIFIED\nVANILLA\nMID I OTWM rVftVOHS\nBaker Extract Co., Springfield, Mass.\nty to enable It to entertain a pro\nceeding criminal or penal in nature\nto enforce statute of the Federal\ngovernment.\"\nTO QUESTION SUSPECTS.\nThree Men Being Hold following\nExplosion in Providence.\nProvidence, R. I., June 24 (UP)\nThree men were to be questioned by\npolice here today in connection with\nthe explosion which wrecked the\nfront of the house at 12 Doyle av\nenue, home of Young Montreal, local\npugilist, Tuesday night.\nThose held were Frank A. Mor\nelli, 30; Francis T. Larkin, 25; and\nCharles Firestin, 35, all of this city.\nPolice believed that the men, who\nwere arrested last night, would be\nable to furnish Important informa\ntion regarding Tuesday's attempt on\nthe life of Young Montreal, and also\ntwo previous attempts in which dy\nnamite was used.\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK.\nImproved Conditions In Carpet In\ndustry are Seen In Thompsonvllle.\nThompsonville. Conn., June 24 (P\nImproved outlook in the carpet\nindustry is given as an explaining of\nthe discontinuance of a ten-day gen\neral shut down for inventory over\nthe Fourth of July period by offi\ncials of the Digelow-Hartford Car\npet company. All weaving depart\nments will continue operations until\nJuly 2 and will resume on July 5.\nIn other departments the layoff\nwill be longer, the worsted mill to\nclose on the 24th, the filling mill the\n28th and the dye house on the 29th,\nbut the entire mill will resume\nJuly 5.\n\"Dead-All Dead\"\nNo Survivors that is the beauty of Black Flag.\nIt kills every fly, mosquito and roach in your home.\nKills other bugs, tool Sold at drug, grocery, hardware\nand department stores. Powder 15c up, and\nfor tftm putt\nLHQUHD\nPint. ,45e\nQuart .85c\nPOWDER \"I.\nLIQUID\nKILLS INGECTO\nSpecial\nSaturday\nEastern Millinery Co.\n133 MAIN ST.\nSpecial\nSaturday\n500 Cew'White Zelts\nON SALE\nTomorrow\nSPECIAL'\n$3-75\nRegular $4.98\nNOT SALE HATS\nbought in a lot to sell at\na price, but carefully\nselected modes from'\nforemost makers of\nhigh-type hats.\nVACATION Days are here, usher\ning in the favored mode of summer\nlight weight Crasher Felts in\nthe much talked of small and me\ndium shapes; all head sizes.\nWhite and\nAll Shades\n$3.75\nGveryone 8s Asking for \"floppy \"ZHats\nOur Assortment is Most Unusual\nMilans Hemps Hairbraid Rough Straws Leghorns\nWhite, Black, Pink, Red, Blue and All Summer Shades\n$3.98 and $4.95\nG. FOX CO., Inc.\nDepartment Store\nHARTFORD, CONN.\nFree Telephone Service From New Britain Call- 3500\nBeach Apparel\none of the sort smart\nwomen are buying\nWomen's Wool Suits\nOne-piece bathing suits of all wool in a splendid\nassortment of colors. Sizes range from 36 to 44.\n$3-98\nWomen's Extra Size Suits\nOne-piece style suits of wool in black with col\nored borders. Sizes 48 to 52.\nChildren's Suits\nOne-piece wool suits without\nskirt. In five different styles\nand in both bright and dark\ncolors. Sizes 2 to 10 years.\n$2-98\nCretonne Coats\nBeach coats in a splendid as\nsortment of colors. Sizes\nsmall, medium and large.\n$2-98\n5 .98\nSpecial\nCOOLE\nCOATS\n1 .98\nGenuine Imported Coolie Coats\nNothing is smarter on the\nbeach than these imported\nCoolie coats of cotton vividly\ndecorated in gay colorings that\nbespeak the Orient. Black and\nnavy with brilliant designs\nespecially chic.\nG. Fox and Co., Tnc Bathing Suits Fourth Floor\nSage -alien (Lvo\ni u\n2-7171 -N Cj j.7171\nHARTFORD\nCome Friday and Saturday (Last TzioDaysJ\nto the\nSemi-Annual Sale of\nSorosis\nFootwear\nBesides the four special value\ngroups listed there are spectacular\nreductions on children's shoes, men's\nand boys' shoes, bathing shoes, rub\nbers, etc.\nSi\nGroup I\nGroup II\n'7-50\nMen's and Boys'\nShoes\nReduced 20'\nAll Children's Shoes\nReduced 20\nBathing Shoes, Keds\nand Rubbers\nReduced 10\nGroup III\nH.85\nGroup JV\n'2.95\nOwing to Factory Restrictions, We Cannot Include the A. E. Little Shoes\nin the Sale.\nWhere a Dollar Has Cents\nBIRNBAUM'S\nEstablish 1911\nDemonstration and Sale\n-of-\nENGLANDER\nBEDS\nEnglander productions\nare nationally known\nfor their quality, and\nare fully guaranteed\nby the manufacturer\nand by us. Special\nprices for this week\nonly.\nSaturday Special\n9 A. M. to 9 P. M\nr ENGLANDER\n5t One Motion Automatic\nDOUBLE DA-BED\n$32-50\nMost unusual offer by the world famous makers of Englander bed products. It\nis only by planning long in advance and by full cooperation of the Englander factory\nthat a great selling event such as ours is made possible. Remember, this sensation\nis for Saturday only!\nThis beautiful Englander Da-Bed with one automatic motion becomes a full size\ndouble bed, equipped with Englander sag-proof and rust-proof link springs. Metal\nends in wood or enamel finish. Handsome cretonne covered mattress, guaranteed by\nEnglander and Birnbaum's to be the best made. Money refunded if vou duplicate\nthis value elsewhere within 30 days.\nNo Mail, Phone or C. O. D. Orders Accepted on this Specia\n381\nMain\nStreet\nBIRNBAUM'S\nBuy Here\nand\nSave","height":"25240","width":"19040"}}
